John Edward: Language skills are important for global citizens
Scottish private schools have remained at the top of the rankings for academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with the following outstanding exam results, reinforced by personal and collective success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
These schools, with more than 30,000 students across Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and their parents.
The purpose of private schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen profession and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a curriculum tailored to the circumstances, we see that modern languages continue to be well-known and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, it comes to his mind.
When you speak to him in his native language, it reaches his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s fresh exam results, we can see that at the top of the tables are the languages with the highest pass rate among private schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a high score of A.
Data collected from a total of 74 SCIS schools show that 72 percent of students scored A in Mandarin, 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign languages as essential skills for life, which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
The languages that are now among the subject choices are in the curricula of private schools and other schools in the same way as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics).
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that 17% of respondents reported a lack of language skills among the reasons why employers find it difficult to find workers for vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future work.
As more promising job offers require language skills, such skills are becoming indispensable in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career choice made, acquiring a second language gives a person a real advantage in the future, as language skills are lifelong.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign nationals gives a multilingual person an immediate competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents do not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation about it. The only language with a two-digit proficiency rate was French with 15 percent.
Therefore, funding for language learning is important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of emerging economies, gives children better opportunities to find a good job.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in each school.
A number of schools focus more on classical modern languages, while other schools teach the languages considered to be the most important in the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, private schools always have the option to choose between several languages taught by experts in their field.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future may bring them.
It can no longer be denied that, in a globalised business environment, languages are crucial for the future of a country, which is why this must also be reflected in education.
It is the modern languages that really should be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Private schools continue to provide young Scots with choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
