Harvard students learn how to get enough rest
This year, Harvard University is offering a new course where students need more sleep to fight a growing aggressive culture of learning through caffeinated night-long learning marathons.
Students who love the academicity of the world’s best university are often helpless when it comes to the basics of taking care of themselves.
According to the designer of this course, Brigham, a sleep doctor at Harvard Medical School, and Charles Czeisler, an expert professor at Women’s Hospital, this is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired by the creation of the course after he gave a speech on how sleep disorders affect learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why is it only now that I am told about this in my final year of school?’
He said that no one had ever told him the importance of sleep — it made me feel bad,” he told the Telegraph.
The course, which first came into the curriculum this year, will explain to students how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic outcomes, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of health care at the university, said the university decided to take a course curriculum after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during their working week.
The hour-long course includes a number of interactional tasks.
A section presents a picture of the dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books, explaining the effects of caffeine and light, how lack of sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of the established practice of going to bed.
The second part explains how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
The map of the campus, along with its interactional symbols, encourages participants to think about their daily habits.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes," Professor Czeisler said.
According to him, there is still pride in the nightly learning marathons, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students rather mean that lack of sleep is still a growing problem.
“Ensuring adequate quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety,” he added. “It even helps against weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain into hunger mode, making a person constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemical and physical biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
Raymond said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to contribute to the creation of a university-wide course.
As a next step, he would like all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set the alarm clock for both going to bed and waking up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” caused by electronic screens and LED lighting, as this could damage their circadian rhythm and cause problems with falling asleep.
